<section xml:id="sec-spheres" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Spheres</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>A <term>sphere</term> is a 3D shape that is perfectly round, like a ball. Basketballs, globes, bubbles, and planets are all approximately spherical.</p>

    <p>Unlike prisms, pyramids, cylinders, and cones, a sphere is completely curved, and has no base, no edges, and no flat faces.</p>

    <p>It turns out that this makes it more complicated conceptually, and requiring more creativity.</p>
  </introduction>

  <!-- ============================== -->
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-sphere-volume">
    <title>Volume of a Sphere</title>

    <p>In fact, the volume of a sphere is</p>

    <example>
      <title>Deriving the Volume Formula</title>
      <p>It turns out, we can derive the volume of a sphere from 2 formulas we already know: the volume of a cylinder and the volume of a cone.</p>

      <p>Consider a sphere, with a radius <m>r</m>. It fits exactly inside a cylinder of radius <m>r</m> and height <m>2r</m> (like a ball in a can).</p>

      <image width="40%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
              % Back elements (behind sphere)
              \draw[dashed, gray] (-2.5,0) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, gray] (-2.5,5) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, gray] (-2.5,0) -- (-2.5,5);
              \draw[dashed, gray] (2.5,0) -- (2.5,5);
              % Sphere (back equator, body, front equator)
              \draw[dashed, blue] (-2.5,2.5) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[thick, blue] (0,2.5) circle (2.5);
              \draw[thick, blue] (-2.5,2.5) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              % Front elements (in front of sphere)
              \draw[dashed, gray] (-2.5,0) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, gray] (-2.5,5) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              % Dimension arrows
              \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,5.8) -- (2.5,5.8) node[midway, above] {$r$};
              \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (3.2,0) -- (3.2,5) node[midway, right] {$2r$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <p>The key fascinating insight is: the volume of the sphere can be thought of as the volume of the entire cylinder, minus the volume of two cones, each with base radius <m>r</m> and height <m>r</m>, placed inside the cylinder with their tips meeting at the center of the sphere.</p>

      <image width="90%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.55]
              % --- Left: cylinder with sphere ---
              % Back elements (behind sphere)
              \draw[dashed, gray] (-2.5,0) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, gray] (-2.5,5) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, gray] (-2.5,0) -- (-2.5,5);
              \draw[dashed, gray] (2.5,0) -- (2.5,5);
              % Sphere (back equator, fill+body, front equator)
              \draw[dashed, blue] (-2.5,2.5) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \fill[blue!10] (0,2.5) circle (2.5);
              \draw[thick, blue] (0,2.5) circle (2.5);
              \draw[dashed, blue] (-2.5,2.5) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[thick, blue] (-2.5,2.5) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              % Front elements (in front of sphere)
              \draw[dashed, gray] (-2.5,0) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, gray] (-2.5,5) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              % Labels
              \node[below] at (0,-0.8) {sphere inside cylinder};

              % --- Equals sign ---
              \node at (5.5,2.5) {\Large $=$};

              % --- Middle: cylinder alone ---
              % Cylinder (red) - fill body and top cap
              \fill[red!10] (7,0) -- (7,5) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7) -- (12,0) arc (360:180:2.5 and 0.7);
              \fill[red!15] (9.5,5) ellipse (2.5 and 0.7);
              % Cylinder (red)
              \draw[thick, red!70!black] (7,0) -- (7,5);
              \draw[thick, red!70!black] (12,0) -- (12,5);
              \draw[thick, red!70!black] (7,0) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, red!70!black] (7,0) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[thick, red!70!black] (7,5) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[thick, red!70!black] (7,5) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \node[below] at (9.5,-0.8) {cylinder};

              % --- Minus sign ---
              \node at (13.5,2.5) {\Large $-$};

              % --- Right: two cones ---
              % Cylinder outline (dashed, gray)
              \draw[dashed, gray] (15,0) -- (15,5);
              \draw[dashed, gray] (20,0) -- (20,5);
              \draw[dashed, gray] (15,0) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, gray] (15,0) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, gray] (15,5) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, gray] (15,5) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              % Cone fills
              \fill[green!10] (15,0) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7) -- (17.5,2.5) -- cycle;
              \fill[green!10] (15,5) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7) -- (17.5,2.5) -- cycle;
              % Bottom cone (tip at center, green)
              \draw[thick, green!50!black] (15,0) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, green!50!black] (15,0) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[thick, green!50!black] (15,0) -- (17.5,2.5);
              \draw[thick, green!50!black] (20,0) -- (17.5,2.5);
              % Top cone (tip at center, green)
              \draw[thick, green!50!black] (15,5) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[thick, green!50!black] (15,5) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[thick, green!50!black] (15,5) -- (17.5,2.5);
              \draw[thick, green!50!black] (20,5) -- (17.5,2.5);
              \node[below] at (17.5,-0.8) {two cones};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <p>To see why, slice all three shapes at the same height. At each level, the sphere's cross-section has the same area as the cylinder's cross-section, minus the cones' cross-section,</p>

      <image width="90%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.55]
              % Slice at y=4 (1.5 above center)
              % Sphere cross-section radius: sqrt(2.5^2 - 1.5^2) = 2
              % Cylinder cross-section radius: 2.5
              % Cone cross-section radius: 1.5

              % --- Horizontal slice plane across all shapes (3D rectangle) ---
              \fill[gray!8] (-3.5,3.5) -- (21,3.5) -- (22,4.5) -- (-2.5,4.5) -- cycle;
              \draw[dashed, gray] (-3.5,3.5) -- (21,3.5) -- (22,4.5) -- (-2.5,4.5) -- cycle;

              % --- Left: Sphere ---
              \draw[blue!80] (0,2.5) circle (2.5);
              \draw[blue!60] (-2.5,2.5) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, blue!20] (-2.5,2.5) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              % Cross-section (filled)
              \fill[blue!25] (0,4) ellipse (2 and 0.56);
              \draw[thick, blue] (-2,4) arc (180:360:2 and 0.56);
              \draw[thick, dashed, blue] (-2,4) arc (180:0:2 and 0.56);
              \node[below] at (0,-0.8) {sphere};

              % --- Equals ---
              \node at (5.5,2.5) {\Large $=$};

              % --- Middle: Cylinder ---
              \draw[red!30!black] (7,0) -- (7,5);
              \draw[red!30!black] (12,0) -- (12,5);
              \draw[red!30!black] (7,0) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, red!20!black] (7,0) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[red!30!black] (7,5) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[red!30!black] (7,5) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              % Cross-section (filled)
              \fill[red!20] (9.5,4) ellipse (2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[thick, red!70!black] (7,4) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[thick, dashed, red!70!black] (7,4) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \node[below] at (9.5,-0.8) {cylinder};

              % --- Minus ---
              \node at (13.5,2.5) {\Large $-$};

              % --- Right: Two cones ---
              \draw[green!30!black] (15,0) -- (17.5,2.5);
              \draw[green!30!black] (20,0) -- (17.5,2.5);
              \draw[green!30!black] (15,5) -- (17.5,2.5);
              \draw[green!30!black] (20,5) -- (17.5,2.5);
              \draw[green!30!black] (15,0) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[dashed, green!20!black] (15,0) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[green!30!black] (15,5) arc (180:360:2.5 and 0.7);
              \draw[green!30!black] (15,5) arc (180:0:2.5 and 0.7);
              % Cross-section (filled)
              \fill[green!25] (17.5,4) ellipse (1.5 and 0.42);
              \draw[thick, green!50!black] (16,4) arc (180:360:1.5 and 0.42);
              \draw[thick, dashed, green!50!black] (16,4) arc (180:0:1.5 and 0.42);
              \node[below] at (17.5,-0.8) {two cones};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <p>This means that the volume of the sphere is the volume of the cylinder, minus the volume of the two cones.</p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>The cylinder has volume,</p>
          <me>V_{\text{cyl}} = \pi r^2 \cdot 2r = 2\pi r^3</me>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>Each cone has base radius <m>r</m> and height <m>r</m>. The total volume of the two cones is,</p>
          <md>
            <mrow>V_{2 \text{ cones}} \amp= 2 \cdot \frac{1}{3}\pi r^2 \cdot r</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp= \frac{2}{3}\pi r^3</mrow>
          </md>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <p>Then, to get the volume of the sphere, subtract the volume of the 2 cones from the volume of the cylinder,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>V_{\text{sphere}} \amp= V_{\text{cyl}} - V_{2 \text{ cones}}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 2\pi r^3 - \frac{2}{3}\pi r^3</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= \frac{4}{3}\pi r^3</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>

    <p>The volume of a sphere is,</p>
    <me>\boxed{V_{\text{sphere}} = \frac{4}{3}\pi r^3 \qquad r \rightarrow \text{radius}}</me>

    <example>
      <title>Volume of a Sphere</title>
      <p>Find the volume of a sphere with radius 3 cm.</p>

      <image width="30%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
              \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (1.5);
              \draw[dashed] (-1.5,0) arc (180:360:1.5 and 0.45);
              \draw[dashed] (-1.5,0) arc (180:0:1.5 and 0.45);
              \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,-2) -- (1.5,-2) node[midway,below] {$3$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <md>
        <mrow>V \amp= \frac{4}{3}\pi r^3</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= \frac{4}{3}\pi(3)^3</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 36\pi</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp\approx 113.1 \text{ cm}^3</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>So, the volume is about 113.1 cm<m>^3</m>.</p>
    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Finding the Radius from Volume</title>
      <p>A sphere has volume <m>288\pi \text{ cm}^3</m>. Find its radius.</p>

      <p>Starting from the volume formula, plug in <m>V = 288\pi</m>,</p>
      <me>\frac{4}{3}\pi r^3 = 288\pi</me>
      <p>We want to solve for <m>r</m>. First, divide both sides by <m>\pi</m>,</p>
      <me>\frac{4}{3} r^3 = 288</me>
      <p>To get rid of <m>\frac{4}{3}</m> on the left, multiply both sides by <m>\frac{3}{4}</m>,</p>
      <me>r^3 = 288 \times \frac{3}{4} = 216</me>
      <p>Finally, to isolate <m>r</m>, take the cube root of both sides,</p>
      <me>r = \sqrt[3]{216} = 6 \text{ cm}</me>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ============================== -->
  <subsection xml:id="subsec-sphere-surface-area">
    <title>Surface Area of a Sphere</title>

    <p>In fact, the surface area of a sphere, is 4 times the area of a circle with the same radius.</p>

    <example>
      <title>Why the Formula Works</title>
      <p>The best way to explore why this formula works, is with this video by 3Blue1Brown: <url href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GNcFjFmqEc8">But why is a sphere's surface area four times its shadow?</url>.</p>
    </example>

    <p>The surface area of a sphere is,</p>
    <me>\boxed{SA_{\text{sphere}} = 4\pi r^2 \qquad r \rightarrow \text{radius}}</me>

    <example>
      <title>Surface Area of a Sphere</title>
      <p>Find the surface area of a sphere with radius 6 cm.</p>

      <image width="30%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
              \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (2);
              \draw[dashed] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.6);
              \draw[thick] (-2,0) arc (180:0:2 and 0.6);
              \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,0) -- (2,0) node[midway,above] {$6$};
              \fill (0,0) circle (1.5pt);
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <md>
        <mrow>SA \amp= 4\pi r^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 4\pi(6)^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 4\pi(36)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 144\pi</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp\approx 452.4 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Surface Area Given Diameter</title>
      <p>A basketball has diameter 24 cm. Find its surface area.</p>

      <p>First, <m>r = \frac{d}{2} = \frac{24}{2} = 12</m> cm. Then,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>SA \amp= 4\pi r^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 4\pi(12)^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 4\pi(144)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 576\pi</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp\approx 1809.6 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <title>Hemispheres</title>
      <p>A <term>hemisphere</term> is half of a sphere. Its volume is <m>V = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{4}{3}\pi r^3 = \frac{2}{3}\pi r^3</m>. Its total surface area includes the curved part (<m>2\pi r^2</m>, half of <m>4\pi r^2</m>) plus the flat circular face (<m>\pi r^2</m>), giving,</p>
      <me>SA_{\text{hemisphere}} = 2\pi r^2 + \pi r^2 = 3\pi r^2</me>
    </remark>

    <example>
      <title>Hemisphere</title>
      <p>Find the total surface area and volume of a hemisphere with radius 8 cm.</p>

      <image width="30%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.6]
              % Flat base
              \draw[thick] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.6);
              \draw[dashed] (-2,0) arc (180:0:2 and 0.6);
              % Top half of sphere
              \draw[thick] (-2,0) arc (180:0:2);
              % Radius
              \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (0,-1) -- (2,-1) node[midway,below] {$8$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      <p>The total surface area is the curved part plus the flat circular base,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>SA \amp= 2\pi r^2 + \pi r^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 2\pi(64) + \pi(64)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 128\pi + 64\pi</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 192\pi</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp\approx 603.2 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>The volume is half the volume of a full sphere,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>V \amp= \frac{2}{3}\pi r^3</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= \frac{2}{3}\pi(8)^3</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= \frac{1024\pi}{3}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp\approx 1072.3 \text{ cm}^3</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Surface Area from Circumference</title>
      <p>A ball has circumference 69.1 cm. Find its surface area.</p>

      <p>First, find the radius from the circumference <m>C = 2\pi r</m>,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>r \amp= \frac{C}{2\pi}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= \frac{69.1}{2\pi}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp\approx 11.0 \text{ cm}</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>Then,</p>
      <md>
        <mrow>SA \amp= 4\pi r^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 4\pi(11.0)^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp= 484\pi</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp\approx 1520.5 \text{ cm}^2</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
  </subsection>

